### Measuring Divergence Impact

The best way to understand divergence is to measure it. Here is a controlled experiment:

```python
@cuda.jit
def divergent(data, out, n):
    idx = cuda.threadIdx.x + cuda.blockIdx.x * cuda.blockDim.x
    if idx < n:
        # Random data -> random branches -> divergence within every warp
        if data[idx] > 0.5:
            out[idx] = data[idx] * data[idx] + 1.0
        else:
            out[idx] = data[idx] * 0.5 - 1.0

@cuda.jit
def non_divergent(data, out, n):
    idx = cuda.threadIdx.x + cuda.blockIdx.x * cuda.blockDim.x
    if idx < n:
        # Branch-free: all threads execute the same arithmetic
        val = data[idx]
        out[idx] = val * val + val * 2.0 + 1.0  # Same work, no branches
```

In practice, the divergent kernel will be measurably slower when data is randomly distributed (50/50 branches) compared to when data is all positive (0% divergence). The difference can range from 10% to 2x depending on how much work is in each branch.

### Nested Divergence: The Nightmare Scenario

```python
@cuda.jit
def nested_divergence(data, out, n):
    idx = cuda.threadIdx.x + cuda.blockIdx.x * cuda.blockDim.x
    if idx < n:
        if data[idx] > 0:
            if data[idx] > 0.5:
                out[idx] = 1.0   # ~25% of threads
            else:
                out[idx] = 0.5   # ~25% of threads
        else:
            if data[idx] > -0.5:
                out[idx] = -0.5  # ~25% of threads
            else:
                out[idx] = -1.0  # ~25% of threads
```

With uniformly random data, this creates **4 divergent paths**. The warp must serialize through all four. Only ~8 threads (25% of 32) are active during each path. You are using only 25% of your hardware -- a 4x slowdown compared to the branchless version.

### Real Error Messages and Silent Failures

Divergence does not produce error messages -- that is what makes it dangerous. Your kernel runs, produces correct results, but takes 2x longer than it should. The only way to detect divergence is measurement:

```
# No error message! This is the insidious part.
# Your divergent kernel:
#   kernel_divergent: 0.45 ms
# Your branch-free kernel:
#   kernel_branchfree: 0.28 ms
#   Slowdown: 1.6x
#
# The ONLY way you know is by benchmarking both versions.
# If you only had the divergent version, you would think 0.45ms is "fast enough."
```

> **Gotcha:** The `if idx < n` boundary check at the start of most kernels IS a divergent branch -- but only for the very last warp in each block. This costs at most 1 warp per block, which is negligible. Do NOT try to eliminate this check. The cure (launching the exact number of threads) is worse than the disease.

> **What would happen if...** every thread in a warp takes a different branch? With 32-way nested branching (each thread takes a unique path), the warp serializes through all 32 paths. Only 1 of 32 lanes is active at any time. You are running at 1/32 of peak throughput -- effectively turning your GPU into a very expensive single-threaded processor.
